## Project Context
filefree.tax starts as a mobile-first free tax prep app — snap a W2, get your completed return in minutes. But the long-term product is an AI financial advisor that uses tax filing as the trust-building entry point. Free filing is the acquisition channel. The AI advisory relationship is the product. Primary audience: first-time and early-career filers (18-30), but the product works for anyone with a simple return.

Two co-founders: Founder 1 (Product/Engineering) builds the app and infrastructure. Founder 2 (Partnerships/Revenue) sources and closes financial product partnerships that drive 77% of revenue. See docs/PARTNERSHIPS.md for the partnerships playbook and docs/STRATEGY_REPORT.md Section 6 for the team structure.

The domain is filefree.tax. The brand name is "FileFree" when written as a product name.

## North Star: Own IRS MeF Transmitter (January 2027)
The ultimate strategic goal is owning our e-file infrastructure at $0/return. We are actively going through the rigorous IRS certification process (EFIN, ATS testing). Until certified, users can download their completed 1040 PDF for free, or e-file via our partner at cost. Once our transmitter passes IRS testing (target: January 2027), e-file becomes free forever.

## Core Philosophy
- "Photo to Done in 5 minutes" — every design decision optimizes for speed and simplicity
- Mobile-first, desktop-responsive
- Dark mode by default with vibrant gradients (Linear/Raycast aesthetic, NOT TurboTax boomer energy)
- AI does the work, user just confirms
- Filing is FREE FOREVER (federal + state) — this is the acquisition channel, never gate it
- Anxiety-killer — every interaction reduces tax stress, never adds to it
- Revenue comes from refund routing to partner accounts (HYSA/IRA), financial product referrals, Tax Optimization Plan ($29/yr), refund advances, and audit shield — NOT from filing fees
- Every screen should build toward the advisory relationship: "FileFree knows my finances and helps me make better decisions"

## Tech Stack (DO NOT DEVIATE)

### Frontend
- **Framework**: Next.js 14+ (App Router)
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Component System**: shadcn/ui (Radix primitives + Tailwind — copy-paste, we own the code)
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS 4+
- **Animations**: Framer Motion
- **AI Streaming**: Vercel AI SDK (`ai` + `@ai-sdk/react`) — for streaming AI insights and explanations
- **Charts**: Recharts
- **Icons**: Lucide React (shadcn default, keep consistent)
- **Forms**: React Hook Form + Zod validation (shadcn Form component wraps this)
- **Server State**: @tanstack/react-query — for all API calls, caching, polling, optimistic updates
- **Client State**: Zustand — for minimal client-only state (auth session, filing step index, theme). NOT for server data.
- **Camera**: Browser MediaDevices API (navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia)
- **PDF Generation**: @react-pdf/renderer (for downloadable tax return PDFs)

### Backend
- **Framework**: FastAPI (Python 3.11+)
- **ORM**: SQLAlchemy 2.0 with async support
- **Database**: PostgreSQL 15+
- **Cache/Sessions**: Redis (used for session storage; add caching later as needed)
- **Async Processing**: FastAPI BackgroundTasks for MVP (migrate to Celery with Redis broker at scale)
- **Migrations**: Alembic

### AI/ML Pipeline — Tiered OCR (Cloud Vision + GPT)
- **OCR Engine**: GCP Cloud Vision API (`DOCUMENT_TEXT_DETECTION`) — returns hierarchical text (pages/blocks/paragraphs/words) with bounding box coordinates. $0.0015/page, 1K free pages/mo. Google does NOT store images or use them for training.
- **Image Preprocessing**: Pillow — auto-rotate (EXIF), contrast normalization, resize to optimal OCR dimensions
- **Field Mapping**: OpenAI GPT-4o-mini (structured outputs) — receives OCR text + positions, maps to W-2 Pydantic schema (~$0.001/doc)
- **Vision Fallback**: OpenAI GPT-4o vision — for low-confidence extractions (<85%), send actual image for direct field extraction (~$0.02/doc)
- **AI Insights**: OpenAI GPT-4o — plain-English tax explanations, personalized tips, advisory content (where quality matters)
- **SSN Isolation**: SSN is extracted via regex from Cloud Vision text output locally — NEVER sent to OpenAI. Masked placeholder (XXX-XX-XXXX) used in all GPT contexts.
- **Blended OCR cost**: ~$0.005/doc (90% handled by Cloud Vision+GPT-4o-mini at $0.002, 10% escalated to GPT-4o vision at $0.02)

### Infrastructure (Zero AWS)
- **Frontend Hosting**: Vercel (Hobby tier, free — upgrade to Pro when needed)
- **Backend Hosting**: Render (Starter plan, $7/mo, 512MB — sufficient for FastAPI making HTTP calls to Cloud Vision/OpenAI)
- **Database (Production)**: Neon serverless PostgreSQL (free tier for MVP, scales to paid at 5K+ users)
- **Sessions (Production)**: Upstash serverless Redis (free tier: 500K commands/mo, sufficient for MVP)
- **File Storage**: GCP Cloud Storage (encrypted, auto-delete via lifecycle policy after 24hrs)
- **Secrets**: Environment variables via .env (never commit)
- **Local Dev**: Docker Compose (postgres, redis, api, web — DEV ONLY, all containerized)
- **Production Deploy**: render.yaml (Render Blueprints IaC) + Vercel git deploy. No production Dockerfiles.
- **Dev Tooling**: Makefile (dev, test, lint, format, migrate), `.python-version` (3.11), `.node-version` (20)
- **No AWS**: All cloud services run on GCP + Render + serverless providers. No AWS account needed.

### Tax Data
- Tax brackets, standard deductions, and credits stored in `api/tax-data/{year}.json`
- Each file includes source citations (IRS Revenue Procedure number, Public Law number)
- 2025 data sourced from Rev. Proc. 2024-40 as amended by P.L. 119-21 (One Big Beautiful Bill)
- Updated annually each October when IRS releases new Revenue Procedure
- Validated against IRS Publication 17 worked examples

### AI UX Patterns (IMPORTANT — this is what makes us feel different)
- AI insights stream in with a typewriter effect using Vercel AI SDK's useCompletion hook
- Show a pulsing "AI thinking" indicator (animated gradient orb) while waiting for AI responses
- Confidence scores on OCR fields use animated color transitions (red → yellow → green)
- The tax summary explanation should stream in word-by-word, not appear all at once
- Use subtle particle/glow effects around AI-generated content to distinguish it from static content
- Every AI interaction should feel fast — optimistic UI, stream partial results, never show a blank loading state

### shadcn/ui Conventions
- Initialize with: `npx shadcn-ui@latest init` (New York style, Slate base color, CSS variables: yes)
- Add components as needed: `npx shadcn-ui@latest add button card dialog input form toast`
- Components live in `src/components/ui/` — this is shadcn's default, don't move them
- Build custom components in `src/components/` — compose from shadcn primitives
- Override shadcn theme in `src/app/globals.css` CSS variables to match our dark indigo/violet brand
- Never install Radix packages directly — always go through shadcn

## Code Style & Conventions

### TypeScript/React
- Use functional components only, never class components
- Use named exports for components, default export only for page components
- File naming: kebab-case for files (e.g., `tax-calculator.ts`), PascalCase for components (e.g., `TaxCalculator.tsx`)
- Directory structure follows Next.js App Router conventions
- All API calls go through @tanstack/react-query hooks wrapping a centralized `lib/api.ts` client
- Use `use client` directive only when necessary (prefer server components)
- All forms use React Hook Form with Zod schemas via shadcn Form component
- Custom hooks go in `hooks/` directory, prefixed with `use`
- Shared types go in `types/` directory

### Python/FastAPI
- Use async def for all route handlers
- Pydantic v2 models for all request/response schemas
- Repository pattern for database access (not raw queries in routes)
- Service layer between routes and repositories for business logic
- All monetary values stored as integers (cents) to avoid floating point issues
- File naming: snake_case everywhere
- Type hints on all function signatures

### Styling Rules
- Mobile-first Tailwind (start with base, add `md:` and `lg:` breakpoints)
- Use CSS variables for theme colors defined in `tailwind.config.ts` and `globals.css`
- Gradient accents: primary gradient is `from-violet-500 to-purple-600`
- Card backgrounds: use shadcn Card component with dark overrides
- Never use arbitrary Tailwind values like `w-[400px]` — use standard utilities
- All interactive elements need hover and focus states
- Minimum touch target: 44x44px for mobile

### Security Rules (CRITICAL — we handle SSNs and financial data)
- NEVER log PII (SSN, full name + address combos, financial data) — implement PII-scrubbing middleware on all log output
- NEVER store W2 images longer than necessary (GCP Cloud Storage lifecycle policy: auto-delete after 24hrs)
- All PII fields encrypted at rest using application-level AES-256 encryption (separate key from DB encryption)
- SSN displayed as masked (XXX-XX-1234) in UI, never fully visible after initial entry
- SSNs are never sent to OpenAI or other LLM providers — W2 images (which may contain SSNs) are sent only to GCP Cloud Vision for OCR; SSNs are regex-extracted locally and masked before any LLM call
- All API routes require authentication except /health, /auth/login, /auth/register, /documents/demo-upload, /waitlist, /api/v1/waitlist
- Rate limit all endpoints: 5 req/min auth, 20 req/min upload, 5 uploads/day/user
- CSRF tokens on all state-changing endpoints (SameSite=Lax cookies require CSRF protection)
- hCaptcha on sign-up to prevent bot abuse
- CORS restricted to frontend domain only
- Input validation on EVERY endpoint using Pydantic models
- Account deletion endpoint available from day one (CCPA/GDPR) — must cascade: Neon DB, GCP Cloud Storage, Upstash sessions
- Never validate SSN against external sources — prevents stolen SSN abuse

## Key Domain Concepts
- **Filing**: A single tax return filing attempt (has status: draft, processing, review, submitted, accepted, rejected)
- **TaxProfile**: User's tax-relevant information extracted from documents
- **Document**: An uploaded document (W2, DL, 1099, etc.) with its extraction results
- **TaxCalculation**: The computed tax return data (income, deductions, credits, refund/owed)
- **Submission**: The e-file submission record with IRS tracking

## API Design
- RESTful with consistent response envelope: `{ success: boolean, data: T, error?: string }`
- API versioning via URL prefix: `/api/v1/`
- Auth via HTTP-only secure cookies with SameSite=Lax + CSRF tokens
- File uploads via multipart/form-data to dedicated upload endpoints
- Long-running operations (OCR) processed via FastAPI BackgroundTasks, client polls for result via react-query

## Error Handling
- Frontend: sonner toast for user-facing errors, never raw error messages
- Backend: Custom exception classes mapped to HTTP status codes, with PII-scrubbed logging
- All errors logged with correlation IDs for debugging
- User-facing error messages are friendly and actionable ("We couldn't read Box 1 on your W2. Try taking another photo with better lighting.")

## Testing
- Frontend: Vitest + React Testing Library for component tests
- Backend: Pytest with async support, factory_boy for test data
- Tax calculation engine: 100% test coverage required (this is financial data, no bugs allowed)
- Validate tax calculations against IRS Publication 17 worked examples
- Integration tests for the full OCR → calculation pipeline
- Linting: Ruff (Python), ESLint (TypeScript)
- Type checking: mypy (Python), tsc --noEmit (TypeScript)
- Dev commands: `make dev` (start), `make test` (run tests), `make lint` (check), `make format` (fix)
